Case Study: UPI / Online Payment Fraud
UPI (Unified Payments Interface) fraud is a rapidly growing cybercrime in which scammers trick people into authorizing payments or revealing sensitive banking details. This type of fraud usually targets students, online shoppers, small business owners, and people who are not fully aware of digital payment safety practices.

A common fraud scenario begins when the victim receives a call, message, or social media link from someone pretending to be a bank official, delivery agent, customer care executive, or buyer/seller. The fraudster creates urgency or trust by offering refunds, prizes, job opportunities, or payment confirmations. Next, the victim is asked to click on a malicious link, scan a QR code, share OTP details, or install a screen-sharing app. In many cases, the scammer sends a “collect request” and convinces the victim that approving it will receive money instead of sending it. Once the victim authorizes the transaction, money is instantly transferred to the fraudster’s account.

The consequences can be severe. Victims may lose their savings within minutes, face emotional stress, and struggle with lengthy complaint and recovery procedures. In some cases, repeated fraud attempts can lead to identity misuse or unauthorized loans.

Preventive measures include never sharing OTPs or PINs, carefully reading payment notifications, avoiding unknown links or apps, and verifying requests directly with official customer support. Digital awareness and cautious behavior are essential to stay safe from UPI fraud.
